==Old English==

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/'wɪtan/}}

===Etymology===
Plural of ''[[wita]]''

====Noun form====
'''witan'''

# [[wise]] men

===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*witan'' (present tense ''*wait-''), from Indo-European ''*u̯oidh₂e'', originally a perfect form of ''*u̯eid-'' ‘see’.  Cognate with Old Frisian ''[[wita]]'', Old Saxon ''[[witan]]''/{{Unicode|'''[[wet|wēt]]'''}} (Dutch ''[[weten]]''), Old High German ''[[wizzan]]''/'''[[weiz]]''' (German ''[[wissen]]''), Old Norse ''[[vita]]''/'''[[veit]]''' (Swedish ''[[veta]]''), Gothic ''[[𐍅𐌹𐍄𐌰𐌽]]''/'''[[𐍅𐌰𐌹𐍄]]'''.  The IE root is also the source of Latin ''[[videre]]'', Baltic ''*waid-'' (Lithuanian ''[[vadinti]]''), Slavic ''*vēde-'' (Old Church Slavonic [[вѣдѣти]], Russian [[ведать]]).

====Preterite-present verb====
'''witan''' (preterite-present: ''3 singular present'' {{Unicode|'''[[wat|wāt]]'''}}, ''3 singular preterite'' '''[[wisse]]''' or '''[[wiste]]''', ''preterite plural'' '''[[wisson]]''' or '''[[wiston]]''', ''past participle'' (ġe)'''[[witen]]''')

# to [[know]] something, to be aware of something

